		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailTitle" style="text-align:center;">
                            Summary on Grant Application Form</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailValue" style="padding:5px;">
                        <span id="lblAbstract">The project will carry out research to determine novel network configurations in microcellular networks, when these are supported by fibre links to/from an area central controller. Such  radio-fibre  techniques allow highly flexible distribution of capacity and collaboration between radio ports to enable soft handover and more generally tailoring of the portable's coverage area to its characteristics such as movement. A network simulator will be developed to enable study of capacity assignment protocols, and macrodiversity radio techniques will be investigated. This will lead to the design and evaluation of system configurations (with associated algorithms) that can cope with high capacity traffic whilst keeping handovers and control traffic to a minimum level. Application to emerging third generation systems (and UMTS in particular) will be considered. The outcome will consist of a set of specific system proposals for  mobility friendly  urban personal communications.</span>
                        </td>
		</tr>
